# Day 08 – Conditional Formatting

## What I Learned
- Learned how to use **Conditional Formatting** to automatically format cells based on specific conditions.
- Applied formatting rules such as color fill, font color, and bold text to highlight important values.
- Understood how conditional formatting helps improve data readability in reports.

## Functions / Features
- **Less Than** → Formats cells when values are below a specified number.
- **Greater Than** → Formats cells when values exceed a specified number.
- **Equal To** → Formats cells when values match an exact value.
- **Text That Contains** → Formats cells based on specific text.
- **Data Bars** → Displays visual bars inside cells to represent values.
- **Duplicate Values** → Highlights duplicate data entries.
- **Color Scales** → Applies gradient colors based on data distribution.

## Practice
- Selected target cells first, then applied conditional formatting rules.
- Used both predefined formats and custom formats for different conditions.
- Created small exercises to visualize data trends and highlight key values.

## Key Takeaways
- Always select the cells to be formatted before applying conditional formatting.
- Conditional formatting rules can be customized based on reporting needs.
- Visual formatting makes it easier to identify patterns, outliers, and duplicates in data.
